Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Marks: 60

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

An online news portal called E-news Express aims to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. Every user who visits the website takes specific actions based on their interest and the company (E-news Express) plans to analyze these actions to understand user interest and determine how to better engage the users of the site.

The executives at E-news Express are of the opinion that there has been a decline in new monthly subscribers compared to the past year because the current webpage is not defined well enough in terms of outline and recommended content to keep customers enaged long enough to make a decison to subscribe.

Objective¶

Based on the criticism from the executives, the design team embarked on a research and created a new landing page that has a new outine and relevant content shown compared to the old landing page.

To test the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers, an experiment was conducted by selecting 100 users randomly and dividing them into two equal groups. The first group called the control grooup was served with the existing landing page and the second group called the treatment group was served with the new landing page and data was collected from both groups based on their interactions with the two versions of the landing page.

As a Data Scientist at E-news express, I have been asked to explore the data and perform statistical analysis (at a significance level of 5%) to determine the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers for the news portal by answering the questions below.

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?

3. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?

4. Is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

Data Dictionary¶

1.user_id - Unique user ID of the person visiting the website.

2.group - Whether the user belongs to the first group (control) or the second group (treatment).

3.landing_page - Whether the landing page is new or old.

4.time_spent_on_the_page - Time (in minutes) spent by the user on the landing page.

5.converted - Whether the user gets converted to a subscriber of the news portal or not.

6.language_preferred - Language chosen by the user to view the landing page.

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

In [231]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5)) # figure to be drawn with a width of 10inches and an height of 5inches
plt.title('boxplot:landing_page vs time_spent_on_the_page') #title of the plot
plt.ylim(0,12) #limit on the y-axis running from 0 to 12
sns.boxplot(x = "time_spent_on_the_page", y = "landing_page", data = df);
plt.show()
print('sample mean =', df['time_spent_on_the_page'].mean())

sample mean = 5.377800000000002

Observation¶

1. The distribution of time spent on old landing pages is a little skewed to the right.

2. Outliers are observed in the time spent viewing the new landing page meaning some individuals wasted little or no time viewing the page while some took ample time viewing the page

3. Individuals spent more time on the new landing page than the old landing page as the median time spent on the new landing page is more than the old landing page

4. We don't know the population mean in this case but the estimated mean from the sample is about 5.37 and we need to carry out statistical test to know if more time was spent on the new landing page or the existing landing page

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let's write the null and alternative hypothesis¶

Let $\mu_1, \mu_2$ be the mean time spent on the old_landing_page and new_landing_page respectively.

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:\mu_2 \leq \mu_1$ i.e the average time spent on the new landing page is less than or equal to the old landing page

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a:\mu_2>\mu_1$ i.e the average time spent on the new landing page is greater than the time spent on the old landing page.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This is a case of a one tailed test for the significance of two means.As the population standard deviation or variance is unknown and we are dealing with a random sample of 100 which has been divided into two and subjecting them to two different pages, this is a case of a two-sample independent t-test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

As given in the problem statement, $\alpha=0.05$

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [232]:
#subsetted data frame for new landing page users 
time_spent_new = df[df['landing_page'] == 'new']['time_spent_on_the_page']

#subsetted data frame for old landing page users
time_spent_old = df[df['landing_page'] == 'old']['time_spent_on_the_page'] ##Complete the code
In [233]:
print('The mean of the time spent on the new page is: ' + str(round(time_spent_new.mean(),2)))
print('The mean of the time spent on the old page is: ' +str(round(time_spent_old.mean(),2)))
print('The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the new page is:', round(time_spent_new.std(),2))
print('The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the old page is:', round(time_spent_old.std(),2))

The mean of the time spent on the new page is: 6.22
The mean of the time spent on the old page is: 4.53
The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the new page is: 1.82
The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the old page is: 2.58

Let's test whether the T-test assumptions are satisfied or not¶

  • Continuous data - Yes, the time spent on the landing page is measured on a continuous scale.
  • Normally distributed populations - Yes, A random sample of 100 divided int two groups of 50 justifies the central limit statistical theorem of sample size greater than 30 so the data can be assumed to be normally distributed.
  • Independent populations - As we are taking random samples and dividing them into two groups and subjecting them to different landing pages,they are said to be independent i.e A TWO SAMPLE INDEPENDENT T-TEST
  • Unequal population standard deviations - As the sample standard deviations are different, the population standard deviations may be assumed to be different.
  • Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample was based on simple random sampling.

Therefore, we can use the two sample T-test for this problem.

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [256]:
#import the required functions
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(time_spent_new, time_spent_old, equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater')
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [235]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.0001392381225166549 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

From the computation above, the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.Therefore, there is enough statistical evidence to say that users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

In [236]:
plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))# figure to be drawn with a width of 7inches and an height of 5inches
plt.title('Barplot: converted vs landing page') #title of the plot

plt.ylim(0,35) #limit on the y-axis running from 0 to 35
plt.xlabel('landing_page') #x-axis title
plt.show()

Observation¶

Most of the users that visited the new landing page were converted while most of the users who visited the old landing page were not converted

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let's write the null and alternative hypothesis¶

Let $p_1, p_2$ be the proportion of users who visited the old_landing_page and new_landing_page respectively.

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:p_2$ $\leq p_1$ i.e i.e the proportion of users who visit the new landing page and get converted is less than or equal to the proportion of users who visit the old landing page and get converted

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a: p_2$ $> p_1$ i.e the proportion of users who visit the new landing page and get converted is greater than the proportion of users who visit the old landing page and get converted

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This is a case of a one tailed test for the significance of two proportions from two samples.As the population standard deviation or variance is unknown and we are dealing with a random sample of 100 which has been divided into two and subjecting them to two different pages, this is a case of a two-sample proportions z-test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

As given in the problem statement, $\alpha=0.05$

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [237]:

 The proportions of converted users from the new and old landing pages are 0.66, 0.42 respectively

Let's test whether the Z-test assumptions are satisfied or not¶

  • Binomially distributed population - YES:people were either converted or not.
  • Random sampling from the population - YES:Sample obtained was a simple random simple divided into two groups
  • Can the binomial distribution approximated to normal distribution - Yes. For binary data, CLT works slower than usual. The standard thing is to check whether np and n(1-p) are greater than or equal to 10. Here, n and p refer to the sample size and sample proportion respectively.

    $np_1 = 50\cdot \frac{33}{50} =33 \geq 10\\ n(1-p_1) = 50 \cdot \frac{50-33}{50} =17 \geq 10 \\ np_2 = 50\cdot \frac{21}{50} =21 \geq 10\\ n(1-p_2) = 50 \cdot \frac{50-21}{50} =29 \geq 10 $

FOR THE CENTRAL LIMIT THEOREM APPROXIMATION TO HOLD¶

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [239]:
# import the required fuction
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest([new_converted_landing_page,old_converted_landing_page],[total_new_page,total_old_page],alternative='larger') 
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.008026308204056278

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [240]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.008026308204056278 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

From the computation above, the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.Therefore, there is enough statistical evidence to say that the conversion rate(the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page is greater than the conversion rate for the old page.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let's write the null and alternative hypothesis¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:$ conversion status is independent of the preferred language.

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a:$ conversion status depends on the preferred language.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This is a case of a determining wether two categorical variables are dependent on one another. In this case the categorical variables are conversion status(YES OR NO) and language preferred (Spanish/French/English). This is a chi-square test of independence.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

As given in the problem statement, $\alpha=0.05$

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This problem involves three population means and a 1-way ANOVA test would be used here provided normality and equality of variance assumptions are verified.

Now, the normality and equality of variance assumptions need to be checked.

  • For testing of normality, Shapiro-Wilks test is applied to the response variable.

  • For equality of variance, Levene test is applied to the response variable.

Shapiro-Wilk’s test¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:$ time spent on the new page follows a normal distribution against

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a:$ time spent on the new page does not follow a normal distribution

In [249]:
# Assumption 1: Normality
from scipy import stats
w, p_value = stats.shapiro(df[df['landing_page'] == 'new']['time_spent_on_the_page']) 

# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.8040016293525696

since the P-value is greater tha 0.05 significance level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and therefore the time spent on page follows a normal distribution

Levene’s test¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0$: All the population variances are equal

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a$: At least one variance is different from the rest

In [250]:
#Assumption 2: Homogeneity of Variance
from scipy.stats import levene

statistic, p_value = stats.levene(
    df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'English')]['time_spent_on_the_page'],
    df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'French')]['time_spent_on_the_page'],
    df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish')]['time_spent_on_the_page'])
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.46711357711340173

Since the p-value is large, we fail to reject the null hypothesis of homogeneity of variances.

Let's test whether the assumptions are satisfied or not¶

  • The populations are normally distributed - Yes, the normality assumption is verified using the Shapiro-Wilks test.
  • Samples are independent simple random samples - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.
  • Population variances are equal - Yes, the homogeneity of variance assumption is verified using the Levene's test.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

As given in the problem statement, $\alpha=0.05$

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [251]:
# separate the time spent on the new page with respect to the three languages preferred
time_spent_English = df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'English')]['time_spent_on_the_page']
time_spent_French = df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'French')]['time_spent_on_the_page']
